# Project Context

Example filled using the `web` repository as a reference. Copy the structure,
not the literal values, into your real `docs/ai/project-context.md`.

<!-- GUIDANCE FOR TEAMS ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## What to put here

Document facts an agent cannot derive on its own at runtime:

- Verified portal entity keys: site friendly URLs, structure/template keys,
  vocabulary IDs, navigation menu names discovered in a previous session.
- Project-specific conventions that differ from the ldev defaults: custom deploy
  sequences, non-standard module paths, monorepo quirks.
- Confirmed OSGi bundle symbolic names for in-repo modules.
- Playwright or browser-automation patterns that work for this project's specific
  login/admin flows (project-specific credential overrides, MFA, SSO).
- Runbooks that were non-obvious or required troubleshooting to produce.

## What NOT to put here

Do not document anything an agent can derive from `ldev ai bootstrap --intent=discover --cache=60 --json`, `ldev context --json`, or
`ldev status --json` at any time:

- Portal URL, OAuth2 credential status, available `ldev` commands, runtime env
  type — all of these are live fields in bootstrap/context output.
- Docker image or Java version if `ldev context --json` already exposes them.
- Step-by-step reproduction of a single bug fix (that belongs in the PR/commit).
- Temporary workaround steps that should become permanent fixes.

Rule of thumb: if an agent can run one `ldev` command and get the answer, it
does not belong here. Reserve this file for stable project knowledge that is
expensive to re-discover.

## When to promote to a vendor or project skill instead

Promote a section to a proper skill when:

- The same procedure applies to more than one project — move it to a vendor skill
  under `templates/ai/skills/`.
- The procedure is long enough to warrant its own `SKILL.md` with step-by-step
  guidance and guardrails — keeping it here makes this file unwieldy.
- The knowledge is a reusable workflow (deploy sequence, migration pattern,
  browser test flow) rather than a stable fact about this specific project.

Keep it here when it is a stable fact unique to this project: a confirmed site
URL, a known structure key, a project-specific path convention.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

## Stack

| Component | Version / detail |
|---|---|
| Product | `web` |
| Platform | Liferay DXP 2025 quarterly |
| Target platform | `2026.q1.0` |
| Docker image | `liferay/dxp:2026.q1.0-lts` |
| Java | 21 |
| Gradle wrapper | 8.5 |
| Node.js | Used locally for tooling and Playwright |
| Browser automation | Playwright |
| Runtime | Local Docker env managed with `ldev` |

## Local Runtime

```bash
ldev doctor
ldev ai bootstrap --intent=develop --cache=60 --json
ldev setup
ldev start
ldev status --json
ldev logs --since 10m --service liferay --no-follow
ldev stop
```

Notes:

- Use `ldev` as the official entrypoint instead of ad hoc Docker commands.
- Prefer JSON output when an agent or script will consume the result.
- If the env is down, verify it with `ldev status --json` before debugging portal behavior.

## Project Layout

- Liferay workspace root: `liferay/`
- Modules: `liferay/modules/`
- Themes: `liferay/themes/`
- Fragments: `liferay/ub-fragments/`
- Journal structures: `liferay/resources/journal/structures/`
- Journal templates: `liferay/resources/journal/templates/`
- ADTs: `liferay/resources/templates/application_display/`
- Migrations: `liferay/resources/journal/migrations/`
- Liferay configs: `liferay/configs/`
- Project docs: `docs/`

## Conventions

- Treat `ldev` output and the code under the repo as the source of truth.
- Keep project-specific AI knowledge in repo-owned docs, not in vendor skills.
- Prefer the smallest deploy or import that proves a change.
- For runtime or portal diagnosis, capture the exact failing command or URL first.

## Glossary

Project-specific terms and the canonical Liferay name they map to. Vendor
skills consume this section via `liferay-expert/references/domain-awareness.md`
to keep naming consistent in briefs, file names, and PR titles.

Format per term: a one-sentence definition, an explicit list of synonyms to
avoid, and the relationships that disambiguate it from neighbours.

```md
**Partner Portal**:
A logical area of the site exposed under `/web/partners` for B2B users.
_Avoid_: tenant, sub-site, microsite.
_Liferay mapping_: Site (group) `partners` with private pages.

**Campaign Article**:
A Web Content Article whose Journal Structure is `CAMPAIGN`.
_Avoid_: campaign post, campaign page, banner content.
_Liferay mapping_: Web Content Article with Structure key `CAMPAIGN`,
template `CAMPAIGN-DEFAULT`.

**Lead Form**:
A multi-step form rendered by the `lead-capture-web` module.
_Avoid_: contact form, registration form.
_Liferay mapping_: OSGi module `lead-capture-web`, portlet
`com.acme.lead.capture.web.portlet.LeadCapturePortlet`.
```

### Relationships (illustrative)

- A **Partner Portal** contains many **Campaign Articles**.
- A **Lead Form** is embedded in a Page via a Widget Page or Display Page Template.
- A **Campaign Article** uses Vocabularies `Region` and `Audience` (Categories,
  not free-form Tags).

### Flagged ambiguities

Capture conflicts here once and resolve them, so the next session does not
re-litigate them:

- "page" was used to mean both a Liferay Page and a Display Page Template —
  resolved: keep "Page" for Liferay Pages, use "Display Page Template" verbatim.
- "user" was used to mean both Liferay User and external Lead — resolved:
  reserve "User" for Liferay accounts; external prospects are "Leads".

### Example dialogue

> **PM:** "When a partner views a campaign, can they download the asset?"
>
> **Dev:** "When a Partner User on the Partner Portal opens a Campaign Article,
> the linked Document Library file inherits the same site permissions. Yes if
> the partner role has VIEW on the Asset Library."

Use a short dialogue here that demonstrates how the project terms compose
naturally. It doubles as a sanity check for new entries: if you cannot write a
realistic sentence with the term, it probably belongs in code, not in the
glossary.

### Rules

- Be opinionated. Pick one canonical project name per concept; list everything
  else as `_Avoid_`.
- Keep definitions tight (one sentence).
- Always include a `_Liferay mapping_` line so the term anchors to a concrete
  Liferay surface (Site / Page / Structure key / Template id / Module / Object
  definition).
- Update inline as terms get resolved during a session — do not batch.
- Drop a term when the codebase no longer uses it.

## Project Runbooks

- Optional: localized admin menu maps for browser workflows:

If your project uses complex or localized back office menus, keep a project-owned
menu map contract under `docs/ai/menu/`:

- `docs/ai/menu/navigation.i18n.json` (entrypoint)
- `docs/ai/menu/menu_admin.i18n.json` (admin/control-panel paths)
- `docs/ai/menu/sidebar_menu.i18n.json` (site-scoped sidebar paths)

Use placeholders (`{site}`, `{siteGroupId}`) and resolve them with:

```bash
ldev context --json
ldev portal inventory sites --json
```

Declare a canonical entrypoint path in this document so agents do not assume
a hardcoded location, for example:

```md
Menu map entrypoint: docs/ai/menu/navigation.i18n.json
```

These files are project-owned context and should be adapted in each repository.

- Build and deploy the smallest affected artifact:

```bash
ldev deploy module <module-name>
ldev deploy theme
```

Use only the command that matches the changed artifact. Do not use broad deploy
or prepare commands as a default validation step.

- Diagnose local runtime before deeper fixes:

```bash
ldev ai bootstrap --intent=troubleshoot --json
ldev status --json
ldev logs --since 10m --service liferay --no-follow
```

- When working on Journal resources, inspect structures, templates, migrations
  and any project-owned skills before changing data-affecting assets.

## Maintenance Notes

- Keep this file factual and updated as the project evolves.
- Remove any section that `ldev ai bootstrap --intent=discover --cache=60 --json` can now answer — it has become
  redundant and will drift.
- If a section becomes generally reusable across projects, move it to a vendor
  skill under `templates/ai/skills/` instead of expanding this file.
